.com\/pr-journal\/bbs7a.jpg\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">b. Press samples between glass slides and secure in place by wrapping wire around the sandwich (Figure 2). Use enough force to secure the sample, but do not flatten sample to a point where you are altering the physiological shape! Do not use this method on soft tissue.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">c. As you complete a sample, place it into its corresponding glass jar that has the 66% DCM\/33% MeOH mixture, place on rocker<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">d. Incubate samples in the 66% DCM\/33% MeOH mixture for <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> on rocker, at room temperature<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">e. While samples are incubating, fill fresh glass jars with 100% DCM <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">f. Once incubation is complete, unwrap the wire used to hold the sandwich together using two pairs of forceps \u2013 this minimizes contact with DCM as you do not want to touch DCM with only bare hands or nitrile gloves! <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">g. As you free up a sample, place it into its corresponding jar that you have filled with 100% DCM<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">h. Wash samples 2x in 100% DCM, <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> each wash, on a rocker at room temperature<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">i. While samples are washing, fill fresh glass jars to the top with dibenzyl ether (DBE) \u2013 this is what your sample will be suspended in for long-term storage<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">j. After step 2h. is complete, transfer samples to their corresponding glass jars that you have filled with DBE<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">k. Thoroughly clean workspace<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"0B166EADEBDD429A809340DA6D18F0B5","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Note:  the following steps describe how to \u201csandwich\u201d your samples. We have found this makes larger specimens more manageable for light sheet microscopy. For example, to prevent excessive curling of the spine in our thoracic samples, we use this technique to straighten out the sample. This reduces the plane depth of the specimen, which helps with imaging larger specimens.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"5AC96F7AC9824C0387FB5AFE857B6FBD","order_id":3,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/bbs7a.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"58D28F6015BC11E9A914CDC116656BA4","order_id":4,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":10800,"title":""}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"AEA0A7B015BC11E9A914CDC116656BA4","order_id":5,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":900,"title":""}},{"id":1054729,"guid":"436FA03320B64B8784A72CBDB93568AB","order_id":6,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Note: Transferring samples from 100% DCM to DBE is time sensitive. The sample will begin to dry out very quickly once removed from 100% DCM.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}},{"id":1054730,"guid":"0B040185BFCB4BF7B736F17D57297081","order_id":7,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":